    fix(ytls/openssl): clear thread-local error queue before SSL I/O
    
    After commit 1cf997e started surfacing real SSL_read errors instead of
    silently swallowing them, production servers began dropping authenticated
    connections with a bogus error:
    
      SSL_read() FAILED ret=-1 ssl_err=1
      error:0200008A:rsa routines::invalid padding
      error:02000072:rsa routines::padding check failed
    
    The error is spurious. The affected connections run TLSv1.3 with X25519
    key exchange and an AEAD cipher ŌĆö OpenSSL never reaches any RSA routine
    during post-handshake reads, so these codes cannot originate in
    SSL_read().
    
    Root cause: between two iterations of flush_clear_data()'s SSL_read
    loop, the on_clear_data_cb callback delivers the IDENTITY_CARD frame up
    to C_AUTHZ, which runs libjwt's EVP_DigestVerify against an RS256 JWT.
    PKCS#1 v1.5 verification trial-decrypts and leaves RSA_R_INVALID_PADDING
    / RSA_R_PADDING_CHECK_FAILED on the thread-local error queue even when
    the signature verifies correctly. On the next SSL_read() the buffer is
    empty and OpenSSL returns <=0; SSL_get_error() then inspects that dirty
    queue (per the documented contract: "The current thread's error queue
    must be empty before the TLS/SSL I/O operation is attempted") and
    misclassifies a benign WANT_READ as SSL_ERROR_SSL. The new error path
    logs the stale RSA code and tears the connection down.
    
    Fix by following the canonical OpenSSL pattern: ERR_clear_error()
    immediately before every SSL_do_handshake(), SSL_write() and SSL_read()
    in this backend. mbedtls is unaffected (no shared error queue).

