    Adds a periodic, self-healing cert-sync path inside c_agent so that
    expired TLS certificates get replaced on every running yuno even when
    the Let's Encrypt deploy-hook silently fails (the production incident
    that motivated the previous hot-reload work).
    
    Mechanism:
    
    * A second C_TIMER child (priv->cert_sync_timer) fires EV_TIMEOUT every
      cert_sync_interval_sec (default 900 s). ac_timeout tells it apart
      from the boot timer by checking `src`.
    
    * On every tick the agent invokes cert_sync_copy_cmd (default
      `sudo -n /yuneta/store/certs/copy-certs.sh` ŌĆö yuneta has NOPASSWD:ALL
      from the .deb postinst). copy-certs.sh runs as root so it CAN read
      /etc/letsencrypt/live/, solving the permission asymmetry between
      certbot and the yuneta user.
    
    * Before and after the copy, the agent snapshots size+mtime of every
      *.crt under cert_sync_store_dir. If either snapshot differs from the
      stored baseline, fresh cert material was copied ŌĆö the agent then
      broadcasts the yuno-level 'reload-certs' command to every running
      yuno via cmd_command_yuno (reusing the existing dispatch) plus the
      local agent itself.
    
    * Stats exposed as read-only SDF_RSTATS attrs: cert_sync_last_check,
      cert_sync_last_action, cert_sync_last_result, cert_sync_failures.
      cmd_cert_sync_status also surfaces /var/lib/yuneta/last-deploy-hook-run
      (written by the deploy hook), so a stale timestamp flags a hook
      failure even before the certs expire.
    
    * Two new agent commands: `cert-sync-now` (force a tick, admin
      override) and `cert-sync-status` (show all of the above).
    
