    picked up by running yunos without restarting the process or tearing down
    live TLS sessions. Motivated by production incidents where the certbot
    deploy hook failed silently and yunos kept serving expiring certificates.
    
    Core changes:
    
    * ytls.h/ytls.c: new public ytls_reload_certificates() API + dispatch
      entry in api_tls_t.
    
    * openssl backend: init() refactored around a new build_ssl_ctx() helper
      so the same code path is used for first init (fatal on error) and
      reload (non-fatal, previous context kept on failure). reload builds a
      fresh SSL_CTX, swaps ytls->ctx, and SSL_CTX_free's the old one; live
      SSL objects keep it alive through their own refcount so no connection
      is disrupted. Adds SSL_CTX_check_private_key() to validate the new
      cert/key pair before swapping.
    
    * mbedtls backend: ytls_t restructured to hold a refcounted
      mbedtls_state_t (conf, cert, pkey, ca_cert) instead of embedding them.
      Each sskt_t takes a ref on creation and releases on free, so live
      sessions keep their pinned state alive even after reload swaps in a
      fresh one. mbedtls_ssl_conf_own_cert() return value is now checked
      (catches key/cert mismatch).
    
    * c_tcp_s.c / c_udp_s.c: expose a public 'reload-certs' command and
      hot-reload automatically when the 'crypto' attribute is written at
      runtime (mt_writing hook).
    
    * c_yuno.c: adds a yuno-wide 'reload-certs' command that walks the gobj
      tree and invokes 'reload-certs' on every running C_TCP_S/C_UDP_S
      listener with use_ssl=TRUE, returning a per-listener report.
    
    * packages/make-yuneta-agent-deb.sh: the Let's Encrypt deploy hook no
      longer restarts the Yuneta stack. It calls
      `ycommand command-yuno command=reload-certs service=__yuno__` to
      hot-reload every yuno, with restart-yuneta left as a fallback if
      ycommand fails. Each step (copy-certs, nginx reload, reload-certs)
      runs independently and logs to /var/log/yuneta/deploy-hook.log, and a
      timestamp is written to /var/lib/yuneta/last-deploy-hook-run so an
      external monitor can detect hooks that never fire.
    
