    Three related changes to the llhttp wrapper used by c_prot_http_sr,
    c_prot_http_cl and c_websocket:
    
    1. Remove the public ghttp_parser_reset() API.  Keeping it was a
       foot-gun: calling it from inside an llhttp callback corrupted the
       parser's state machine (the pipelining bug already landed in the
       previous CHANGELOG entry).  Callers that need a pristine parser
       for a new connection now go through the destroy+create cycle in
       ac_connected ŌĆö the llhttp state machine is always fresh.
    
    2. New ghttp_parser_finish() that signals end-of-stream to llhttp.
       Fixes a latent bug where HTTP/1.0 responses (and HTTP/1.1
       Connection: close responses without Content-Length) never fired
       on_message_complete because the peer socket close was the only
       message terminator.  Wired up in ac_disconnected of the HTTP
       client, HTTP server and websocket gclasses.
    
    3. On HPE_PAUSED_UPGRADE, ghttp_parser_received() now returns the
       actual bytes llhttp consumed (via llhttp_get_error_pos()) instead
       of pretending it consumed the whole buffer.  Callers can now
       re-route the tail to the next protocol handler (e.g. a WebSocket
       frame piggy-backed on the upgrade TCP segment).
    
    Also: the llhttp settings vtable is initialised via llhttp_settings_init()
    (lazy, once, on first ghttp_parser_create) instead of relying on a C99
    designated initializer ŌĆö makes the intent explicit and future-proof
    against llhttp adding new callback slots.
    
