    fix(c_auth_bff): kc_watchdog cancel/restart race on back-to-back tasks
    
    ac_end_task called clear_timeout0(kc_watchdog), which posts a CANCEL
    SQE and transitions the timer to CANCELING.  process_next() then runs
    synchronously below for any queued request and would call set_timeout0
    to arm the watchdog for the next task ŌĆö but yev_start_timer_event
    refuses to start an event in CANCELING state ("cannot start timer: is
    CANCELING") because the cancel CQE hasn't drained yet.
    
    Symptom: test8_queue_full pipelines 4 POSTs through a queue of size 2.
    After POST 1's KC round-trip completes and ac_end_task runs, POST 2
    is dispatched in the same loop iteration ŌåÆ process_next ŌåÆ set_timeout0
    ŌåÆ error.  POST 2 then never gets its watchdog and the chain breaks.
    
    Fix: stop cancelling the watchdog at all on natural completion.
    
      - Add priv->kc_watchdog_armed: TRUE between process_next and
        ac_end_task, FALSE outside that window.
    
      - process_next sets armed=TRUE before set_timeout0.  set_timeout0
        on a still-RUNNING timer just calls timerfd_settime to reset the
        expiration (the YEV_ST_RUNNING fast path in yev_start_timer_event,
        no cancel SQE), so back-to-back arms work.
    
      - ac_end_task only clears armed=FALSE ŌĆö does NOT clear_timeout0.
        If there's no next task, the timer keeps running with stale
        duration; ac_kc_watchdog ignores stale fires via the armed check.
    
      - ac_kc_watchdog bails out early when !armed (stale fire) and
        otherwise clears armed before doing its work, so a second
        spurious fire can't double-trigger.
    
    mt_stop still cancels normally (shutdown path is single-threaded so
    the cancel CQE has time to drain before destroy).
    
