    fix(ghttp_parser): don't llhttp_init() from inside on_message_complete
    
    on_message_complete() called ghttp_parser_reset(parser), which calls
    llhttp_init(&parser->llhttp, ...) ŌĆö and llhttp_init zeroes the parser's
    internal state machine (cs/sp/return-stack).  We are still inside
    llhttp_execute when this fires, about to return 0 from the callback so
    llhttp can keep parsing the rest of the buffer.  Re-initialising llhttp
    from inside its own callback corrupts that state and llhttp silently
    swallows every subsequent message in the same buffer.
    
    Symptom: test8_queue_full pipelines four POSTs back-to-back on one TCP
    connection, the BFF receives all four chunks on the wire, but only the
    first one ever fires EV_ON_MESSAGE.  Tests 1-7/9-11 don't trip it
    because none of them pipeline.  Production yunos doing HTTP keep-alive
    with pipelined requests would hit the same bug.
    
    Fix: in on_message_complete, replace ghttp_parser_reset(parser) with an
    inline reset of the per-message app fields (url, headers, body,
    cur_key, last_key, body_size, headers_completed, message_completed) ŌĆö
    without touching llhttp.  llhttp handles message-to-message transitions
    internally for keep-alive; we just have to clear our own bookkeeping.
    ghttp_parser_reset() is left intact for its other callers (create-time
    init, ac_connected, parse error path) where calling llhttp_init is the
    correct thing to do.
    
