    fix(c_auth_bff): add outbound Keycloak watchdog timer
    
    Closes the "Keycloak hangs ŌåÆ BFF channel wedged forever" scenario
    that would otherwise be a permanent deadlock under the current BFF
    design.  Previously, if the outbound c_prot_http_cl to Keycloak
    accepted the TCP but never received a reply, priv->processing
    stayed TRUE indefinitely, the queue would fill to pending_queue_size
    and every subsequent request would 503.  A single silent upstream
    could take an entire BFF channel off the air.
    
    The fix is a per-instance C_TIMER0 watchdog that arms when a
    Keycloak round-trip starts and disarms on normal completion.  If it
    fires first, the BFF counts a timeout, responds 504 to the browser,
    and triggers the standard ac_end_task cleanup path so the next
    queued request can be dispatched.
    
    New surface
    ===========
    - attr `kc_timeout_ms` (SDF_RD, default 30000, 0 = disabled).  Per-
      instance knob so high-latency backends (Keycloak behind WAF / over
      the WAN) can raise the ceiling; 0 opts out entirely for deployments
      that prefer an external supervisor.
    - stat `kc_timeouts` (exposed via mt_stats + __reset__).  Lets
      dashboards tell "the upstream is slow" apart from "the upstream is
      rejecting requests" (kc_errors) or "the browser gave up"
      (responses_dropped).
    
    PRIVATE_DATA additions
    ======================
    - `hgobj kc_watchdog`          ŌĆö C_TIMER0 child, created in mt_create,
                                      started in mt_start, stopped in
                                      mt_stop, armed in process_next,
                                      cleared in ac_end_task.  C_TIMER0
