                   - set kc_watchdog_fired = TRUE for the race gate
                   - gobj_send_event(gobj, EV_END_TASK, 0, gobj) to
                     reuse ac_end_task's existing cleanup path rather
                     than duplicating it here
    ac_end_task:   clear_timeout0(kc_watchdog), reset
                   kc_watchdog_fired and active_browser_src, then the
                   existing stop-gobj_http / processing=FALSE /
                   process_next logic.
    result_token_response / result_kc_logout:
                   at the very top, before touching output_data or
                   counters: if kc_watchdog_fired, drop the reply via
                   CONTINUE_TASK.
    
    FSM + event_types[]:
                   EV_TIMEOUT added to both, dispatching to
                   ac_kc_watchdog.  Previously c_auth_bff had no timer
                   children so EV_TIMEOUT was unused.
    
    Semantics
    =========
    - Happy path is byte-identical to before when kc_timeout_ms is
      never reached: watchdog armed in process_next, disarmed in
      ac_end_task, the watchdog fields never written.
    - kc_timeout_ms=0 disables the watchdog entirely ŌĆö no set_timeout0
      is ever called, so the test7 / test9 / test11 scenarios behave
      exactly the same.
    - The 504 response goes through send_error_response which
      increments st_bff_errors (consistent with other error paths).
      Dashboards that want to separate "upstream too slow" from "other
      4xx/5xx" can compare st_kc_timeouts against st_bff_errors.
    
    Exercised by test10_kc_silence in the following commit, which sets
    kc_timeout_ms=500 on the BFF and latency_ms=60000 on the mock
    Keycloak.

