    Follow-up to test9_browser_cancel.  test9 proved the BFF drops the
    stale KC reply; test11 proves the BFF instance is left in a clean
    enough state to handle the NEXT request correctly.
    
    Rationale
    =========
    After the browser_alive gate fires in result_token_response, several
    pieces of BFF state have to recover for the next request:
    
      - priv->gobj_http  ŌåÆ cleared by ac_end_task (otherwise the
                           invariant guard in process_next fires)
      - priv->processing ŌåÆ reset to FALSE
      - q_count etc.     ŌåÆ no leaked entries from the cancelled request
      - browser_alive    ŌåÆ flipped back to TRUE on the next EV_ON_OPEN
    
    test11 exercises all four by driving two sequential /auth/login
    posts on the same C_AUTH_BFF instance: the first one is cancelled,
    the second one must complete cleanly.
    
    Setup
    =====
    Same topology as test9 ŌĆö persistent_channels=true on __bff_side__ so
    the C_CHANNEL survives the disconnect and the second TCP connection
    lands on the same C_AUTH_BFF, not a fresh one.  Mock KC latency_ms
    stays at 500.
    
    Timeline (anchored at mt_play)
    ==============================
      t = 0     mt_play ŌåÆ 300 ms warm timer
      t = 300   open http_cl #1
      t Ōēł 300   POST #1, arm 100 ms cancel timer
      t Ōēł 300   mock KC arms 500 ms latency timer
      t = 400   cancel timer ŌåÆ stop_tree(http_cl #1), arm 800 ms retry
      t Ōēł 400   BFF ac_on_close ŌåÆ browser_alive = FALSE
      t Ōēł 800   mock KC latency fires ŌåÆ BFF result_token_response ŌåÆ
                kc_ok++ ŌåÆ gate ŌåÆ responses_dropped++ ŌåÆ CONTINUE_TASK
      t Ōēł 800   ac_end_task ŌåÆ priv->gobj_http = NULL, processing = FALSE
      t = 1200  retry timer ŌåÆ open http_cl #2 on a fresh TCP to the same
                BFF channel
      t Ōēł 1200  BFF ac_on_open ŌåÆ browser_alive = TRUE
      t Ōēł 1200  POST #2 ŌåÆ enqueue ŌåÆ dispatch ŌåÆ mock KC arms a NEW 500 ms
                latency timer
      t Ōēł 1700  mock KC latency #2 fires ŌåÆ BFF result_token_response ŌåÆ
                kc_ok++ ŌåÆ gate TRUE ŌåÆ send_json_response ŌåÆ browser gets
                200 OK with the mockuser claims
      t Ōēł 1700  driver EV_ON_MESSAGE ŌåÆ validate + verify_and_die
      t Ōēł 1800  death timer ŌåÆ set_yuno_must_die
    
    Retry delay choice
    ==================
    The retry is 800 ms, NOT 100-200 ms.  That is deliberate:
    
    The BFF's browser_alive flag is a single BOOL per instance, not
    per-connection.  If the second EV_ON_OPEN arrives BEFORE the first
    request's result_token_response runs, browser_alive would be
    flipped back to TRUE while a stale task is still in flight.  The
    gate in the stale task would then see TRUE and forward its reply
    to the NEW connection ŌĆö delivering the WRONG user's token to the
    second browser.
    
    At 800 ms the retry lands AFTER the stale reply has been drained
    through the gate, so state is clean by the time the second EV_ON_OPEN
    arrives.  This sidesteps the per-connection race rather than
    exposing it ŌĆö exposing that race is a future test (t12) paired
    with a stronger fix in c_auth_bff (per-task browser identity or
    task-side cancellation at ac_on_close).  test11 documents the race
    in a big comment at the top of the file for follow-up.
    
    Asserted expected state
    =======================
    BFF:
      requests_total     = 2
      kc_calls           = 2
      kc_ok              = 2   (mock KC replied 200 both times)
      kc_errors          = 0
      bff_errors         = 0
      responses_dropped  = 1   (only the first)
      q_full_drops       = 0
    
    Mock KC:
      token_requests     = 2
      responses_sent     = 2
      deferred_responses = 2
      pending_cancelled  = 0
    
