    fix(c_auth_bff): drop KC reply when browser disconnected mid-round-trip
    
    Root cause of the sporadic failure pattern that motivated the whole
    auth_bff test suite: a browser that cancels a login / refresh / logout
    in the window between "BFF forwards to Keycloak" and "Keycloak replies"
    left the BFF trying to write the eventual 2xx response into a
    c_prot_http_sr whose TCP half was already torn down.
    
    What used to happen
    ===================
    ac_on_close on the browser-side c_prot_http_sr just logged and
    returned.  The outbound Keycloak round-trip kept running.  When it
    eventually came back, result_token_response / result_kc_logout read
    browser_src from output_data (raw hgobj pointer) and called
    send_json_response ŌåÆ gobj_send_event on it.  Depending on lifecycle
    timing that was either:
      - a "gobj DESTROYED" gobj_log_error (noisy, breaks any test with
        empty expected_results), or
      - a write into the http_sr + its now-childless c_tcp that silently
        dropped the bytes but logged "Destroying a RUNNING gobj" at
        channel teardown, or
      - in the worst case, a dangling pointer read if persistent_channels
        happens to have freed the subtree.
    
    The test9_browser_cancel in the following commit reproduces this
    deterministically with mock-KC latency_ms=500 and a driver that
    aborts its http_cl at 100 ms.
    
    Minimal fix
    ===========
    Add a per-instance BOOL browser_alive to PRIVATE_DATA.
    
      - ac_on_open    ŌåÆ browser_alive = TRUE.
      - ac_on_close   ŌåÆ browser_alive = FALSE.  Queue is intentionally
                        not cleared in this commit: by construction every
                        queued PENDING_AUTH belongs to the same browser
                        (one c_prot_http_sr per C_AUTH_BFF instance), so
                        the drain loop in result_* will skip each of them
                        via the same gate.
      - result_token_response
                      ŌåÆ after counting kc_ok/kc_errors and emitting the
                        TRACE_MESSAGES/TRACE_TRAFFIC traces (so the
                        Keycloak reply still shows up on the operator's
                        timeline), check browser_alive.  If FALSE bump
                        st_responses_dropped, log a trace message, and
                        CONTINUE_TASK so the task finishes normally and
                        ac_end_task runs its standard cleanup path.
      - result_kc_logout
                      ŌåÆ same gate, mirrors the same semantics.
    
    New stat counter: st_responses_dropped, wired into mt_stats and
    honoured by the __reset__ path.  Charts and tests can now tell
    "browser cancelled" apart from "Keycloak errored" ŌĆö the former
    increments responses_dropped without touching kc_errors; the latter
    increments kc_errors without touching responses_dropped.
    
    Nothing else changes: ac_end_task still tears down priv->gobj_http,
    processing still flips back to FALSE, the c_task state machine walks
    the two-job chain to completion.  Fast-path happy cases are byte-
    identical to before ŌĆö browser_alive is TRUE throughout, the gate is
    a single read, CONTINUE_TASK is never triggered.
    
    Caveat
    ======
    ac_on_close does not proactively tear down the in-flight outbound
    priv->gobj_http.  The Keycloak round-trip will still complete (mock
    KC sees responses_sent=1 in the test) and only then be swallowed by
    the gate.  A more aggressive fix would cancel the outbound too, but
    that raises questions about Keycloak session state (a /logout that
    the BFF initiated and then aborted leaves the refresh token live),
    so it is out of scope for this commit.

