    for every F2-family test (slow login, queue contention, browser
    cancel during KC, KC total silence, cancel-then-retry).
    
    New surface
    ===========
    - attr `latency_ms` (int, SDF_RD, default 0).  When > 0 the mock
      stashes the response in a single pending slot and arms an internal
      C_TIMER child instead of replying from ac_on_message.  Default 0
      preserves the synchronous behaviour the F1-a/F1-b tests depend on.
    - stats: `deferred_responses`, `pending_cancelled` ŌĆö track the new
      code path; unused counters stay at 0 for the existing tests, so
      their assertions remain untouched.
    
    Implementation
    ==============
    - PRIVATE_DATA grows a timer handle plus a pending_{src, status,
      status_text, body} slot.  The slot is single-entry on purpose: a
      real Keycloak instance serialises one request per BFF outbound
      connection, so a second pending means the test is driving the
      mock wrong ŌĆö we log a gobj_log_error and drop the previous one.
    - mt_create creates the timer child (always, zero-cost when unused
      so ac_on_message can be unconditional).
    - mt_destroy / mt_stop decref a lingering pending_body to keep the
      memory leak check clean.
    - `mk_send_json` is unchanged (still the synchronous primitive).
      New helper `respond_or_defer` wraps it: if latency_ms == 0 it
      calls mk_send_json and decrefs the body immediately; otherwise it
      moves ownership into the pending slot and arms the timer.
    - ac_on_message switches from calling mk_send_json directly to
      calling respond_or_defer.  JSON_DECREF on the body moves into
      respond_or_defer (synchronous path) or ac_timer (deferred path);
      ac_on_message no longer touches jn_body ownership.
    - New `ac_timer` action sends the stashed response and clears the
      slot.  Wired into st_idle + event_types[] under EV_TIMEOUT.
    - `ac_on_close` now checks whether the closed src matches the
      pending slot; if so it cancels the timer, drops the body, bumps
      `pending_cancelled`.  Pre-empts the "timer fires into a destroyed
      c_prot_http_sr" race that test9_browser_cancel will exercise next.
    
    Caveats / future work
    =====================
    - Single pending slot, not re-entrant.  A second concurrent request
      with latency_ms > 0 logs an error; future F2 tests that need
      parallel deferred responses will have to lift this.
    - No "drop after accept" / "send partial body" chaos knobs yet;
