    feat(c_auth_bff): make pending queue size configurable via attr
    
    Replace the hardcoded MAX_PENDING_QUEUE=16 with a per-instance attr
    `pending_queue_size` (SDF_RD, default 16, clamped to [1, 1024]).
    
    Motivation
    ==========
    The auth_bff yuno is expected to handle intensive traffic on the
    front-line (browser login storms), but different deployments have
    different load profiles.  A hardcoded 16-slot ring is:
      - too small for public login endpoints under burst
      - perfectly fine for internal, low-rate BFFs
    so the right answer is per-instance tunability without recompile.
    
    Changes
    =======
    - New SDATA entry `pending_queue_size` (DTP_INTEGER, SDF_RD,
      default "16") with a description stating the clamp range.
    - DEFAULT_PENDING_QUEUE_SIZE = 16, MAX_PENDING_QUEUE_SIZE = 1024.
      The ceiling is a safety cap so a misconfigured attr can't silently
      allocate gigabytes; PENDING_AUTH is ~9 KB per entry, so 1024 slots
      ~= 9 MB per channel, which is already a lot for a BFF instance.
    - PRIVATE_DATA: `PENDING_AUTH queue[MAX_PENDING_QUEUE]` becomes
      `PENDING_AUTH *queue` + `int queue_size`.
    - mt_create reads the attr, clamps, and allocates the ring via
      GBMEM_MALLOC (calloc-backed, so entries are zero-initialised for
      free).  An out-of-range value is clamped to the ceiling with a
      gobj_log_warning so operators see it.
    - mt_destroy frees the ring.
    - enqueue/dequeue and cmd_view_status replace every MAX_PENDING_QUEUE
      reference with priv->queue_size.  view-status's q_max field now
      reports the runtime size, so operators see the real limit.
    - The enqueue full-queue log line now includes queue_size so the
      operator immediately knows which ring filled.
    
    No behaviour change for existing callers: the default is 16,
    identical to the old constant.
    
    Prepares the ground for the stress/perf suite (tests/c/c_auth_bff,
    stress/c/auth_bff, performance/c/perf_auth_bff) where the test will
    configure small queues (to exercise the 503 path deterministically)
    and the perf benchmark will sweep large queues to measure the
    throughput ceiling per channel.

