    fix(c_auth_bff): prefix + case-insensitive filters for mt_stats and redact_for_trace
    
    Two post-review fixes surfaced while re-reading the auth_bff thread.
    
    1. mt_stats filter now mirrors stats_parser.c properly
    ===============================================
    
    The previous mt_stats override only implemented the first of the two
    stages the default parser does:
    
        strstr(stats, it->name)
    
    stats_parser.c::_build_stats() falls back to a second stage when the
    first one fails ŌĆö it extracts the stat's own prefix up to the first
    '_' and looks for THAT inside the caller-provided filter, which is
    what makes ad-hoc filters like "kc_" or "kc" match every kc_* counter.
    
    Without that fallback, gobj_stats(bff, "kc_", ...) returned an empty
    dict on this GClass while it would have returned all four kc_*
    counters via the default parser.  The commit message of ff45d5d
    claimed "same prefix-matching as stats_parser.c" but the code only
    replicated half of it.
    
    Add a PRIVATE stats_match() helper that does both stages and use it
    from the STAT_INT macro.  Both lookups now go through strcasestr so
    "KC", "BFF", "Q", ŌĆ” work the same as the lowercase canonical names.
    
    2. redact_for_trace is case-insensitive
    =======================================
    
    Keys were matched exactly against a hardcoded list that mixed
    lowercase ("password", "code", ŌĆ”) with uppercase ("COOKIE").  If the
    HTTP stack ever delivered headers as "Cookie" or "cookie" the raw
    value would have slipped into the trace unredacted; and if the
    browser client sent "PASSWORD" in the JSON body it would have leaked
    too.
    
    Rewrite the function in two passes:
    
      - Pass 1 walks the deep-copied object with json_object_foreach,
        compares each key against a single unified secret_keys[] list
        using strcasecmp, and snapshots any matches into a stack buffer
        (mutating the object during iteration is not safe).
      - Pass 2 replaces each matched value with the "<N chars>" marker.
    
    "cookie" is folded into secret_keys[] as a regular entry, so the
    special-case COOKIE lookup is gone.
    
    Verified with a standalone unit test covering both functions:
    
      - stats_match():     27/27 cases pass (empty filter, exact name,
                            prefix fallback, case-insensitive variants,
                            negative matches).
      - redact_for_trace(): 8/8 cases pass (lowercase/UPPERCASE/MixedCase
                            keys, multiple secrets, non-string values
                            left alone, NULL input, non-object input).
    
    Includes <strings.h> for strcasecmp (strcasestr was already usable
    via the build's _GNU_SOURCE defaults, as ghttp_parser.c demonstrates).

