    perf(c_auth_bff): move stats to PRIVATE_DATA + mt_stats for zero hot-path cost
    
    Replace the eight SDF_RD|SDF_RSTATS counter attributes added in the
    previous commit with plain uint64_t fields in PRIVATE_DATA, and
    implement the global method mt_stats to expose them on demand. Each
    increment on the request path is now a single `priv->st_xxx++`
    instead of two SDATA round-trips (string lookup + JSON read + JSON
    write), which matters for a gobj that may handle thousands of
    requests per second per channel.
    
    What changed in the file
    ========================
    
    - attrs_table: removed the 8 SDF_RSTATS entries (requests_total,
      q_count, q_max_seen, q_full_drops, kc_calls, kc_ok, kc_errors,
      bff_errors). attrs_table is back to just the configuration knobs.
    - PRIVATE_DATA: added 7 uint64_t st_* fields. q_count stays as the
      existing int (it's a live gauge, mirrored as-is in mt_stats).
    - incr_stat() helper: removed. Every call site now does
      priv->st_xxx++ directly (enqueue, dequeue, process_next,
      result_token_response, result_kc_logout, send_error_response, plus
      the q_full_drops path inside enqueue).
    - mt_stats: new global method, wired into gmt. Honours the standard
      "__reset__" stat name (zero the resettable counters; q_count is a
      gauge so it's left alone; q_max_seen is anchored to the current
      q_count so the new high-water mark starts from "now"). Honours the
      prefix filter convention with strstr(stats, name) ŌĆö mirror of what
      stats_parser.c does for SDF_*STATS attributes ŌĆö so
      `gobj_stats(child, "kc_", ...)` returns only the kc_* counters.
      Builds the dict on demand from priv fields and returns via
      build_stats_response.
    - Added #include <stats_parser.h> for build_stats_response.
    
    Yuneta architectural rules reinforced in this session
    =====================================================
    
    The auth_bff thread covered several conventions worth recording in
    the commit history so they're visible from anywhere (claudia gui
    included). They are also persisted in this assistant's memory so
    future edits respect them.
    
    1. NO SILENT ERRORS
    
       Every Yuneta C function path that returns an error indicator
       (-1, NULL, FALSE) MUST do one of two things:
    
         (a) Call gobj_log_error(...) immediately before the return
             with the standard fields (function, msgset, msg, plus
             context attrs).
         (b) If the failure was already logged by the helper that
             produced it (gobj_find_service("name", TRUE),
             kw_get_* with KW_REQUIRED, gobj_create_* on failure, ...)
             write `// Error already logged` on its own line right
             above the return.
    
       The annotation is mandatory, not optional. A bare `if(!x)
       return -1;` with no log and no comment is a defect, not a
       stylistic choice. Silent errors waste hours of investigation
       and undermine the whole observability story of the framework.
    
       Applied here: send_error_response() now emits a gobj_log_error
       with status, status_text, error and browser_src on every call,
       covering the 12 4xx/5xx callsites in c_auth_bff.c that were
       previously silent on the server side.
    
    2. GCLASS PUBLIC INTERFACE = attrs / commands / events / lmethods / stats
    
       The .h of a GClass exposes ONLY two things:
    
         - GOBJ_DECLARE_GCLASS(C_FOO);
         - PUBLIC int register_c_foo(void);
    
       Anything else ŌĆö including PUBLIC accessor functions like
       `c_foo_get_state(hgobj)` ŌĆö is a layering violation. Other code
       interacts with a gclass exclusively through one of these five
       uniform mechanisms:
    
         1. Attributes  ŌĆö SDATA in attrs_table; gobj_read_*_attr /
                           gobj_write_*_attr. For typed configurable
                           state.
         2. Commands    ŌĆö SDATACM in command_table; invoked by other
                           gobjs via gobj_command(target, name, kw,
                           src) and unwrapped from the standard
                           {result, comment, schema, data} envelope.
                           Also reachable from the agent via ycommand.
                           Use for synchronous queries / operations
                           that should also be human-callable.
         3. Events      ŌĆö entries in event_types[]/states[]; sent via
                           gobj_send_event / gobj_publish_event. For
                           async notifications and message flows.
         4. Local methods (LMETHOD) ŌĆö entries in lmt[]; called via
                           gobj_local_method. For tight inter-gobj
                           plumbing without a human use case (e.g.
                           c_task calling action_*/result_* on its
                           owner).
         5. Statistics  ŌĆö see rule 3 below. For numeric counters /
                           rates / gauges.
    
       That uniformity is what makes the framework introspectable,
       controllable from the agent, and debuggable in production.
    
       Applied here: c_auth_bff.h is back to just GOBJ_DECLARE_GCLASS
       + register_c_auth_bff. The previous draft's
       c_auth_bff_get_status() raw accessor was replaced by a
       view-status command in command_table; the yuno aggregator
       (C_AUTH_BFF_YUNO::view-bff-status) walks every C_AUTH_BFF child
       under __bff_side__ via gobj_match_children_tree and queries
       each one through gobj_command(child, "view-status", ...). Same
       information, idiomatic channel.
    
    3. STATISTICS ŌĆö TWO IMPLEMENTATIONS, PICK BY HOT-PATH FREQUENCY
    
       gobj_stats(gobj, prefix, kw, src) is the entry point for
       collecting metrics. It checks whether the gclass implements
       mt_stats; if yes, mt_stats wins and the default parser is
       bypassed (see gobj_stats() in gobj.c around line 4894).
    
       Two implementations are valid:
    
       (a) DEFAULT PARSER, via SDF_STATS / SDF_RSTATS / SDF_PSTATS
           attributes in attrs_table[].
    
           Convenient and zero-code: declare counters with the right
           SDF_* flag, increment via gobj_write_integer_attr. The
           framework's stats_parser walks them automatically and the
           standard "__reset__" stat name resets the resettable ones.
           Good for low-rate metrics where SDATA overhead is in the
           noise.
    
       (b) CUSTOM mt_stats, with counters as plain uint64_t fields in
           PRIVATE_DATA.
    
           Required for high-traffic gobjs. Every SDF_*STATS increment
           goes through SDATA (string lookup, JSON read, JSON write)
           which is non-trivial cost per request. With mt_stats you
           keep the counters as raw struct fields (single
           priv->stat++) and pay the JSON cost only on demand inside
           mt_stats.
    
           Conventions to honour so callers see no difference:
             - "__reset__" zeroes the resettable fields.
             - empty/NULL stats arg returns all stats.
             - non-empty stats arg filters with strstr(stats, name) ŌĆö
               same prefix-matching as stats_parser.c lines 122-135.
             - Return value via build_stats_response(gobj, 0, 0, 0,
               jn_data) so the envelope matches the default parser.
    
       This commit converts c_auth_bff from path (a) to path (b) for
       exactly that reason: it sits in the auth flow of every browser
       request, with up to 25 channels in __bff_side__, and every
       request crosses several increment points (enqueue,
       process_next, result_*, optional send_error_response). Plain
       field bumps remove that overhead entirely.
    
    Hot-path comparison
    ===================
    
    Before (SDF_RSTATS attribute):
        incr_stat(gobj, "kc_calls");
            Ōåō
        gobj_write_integer_attr(gobj, "kc_calls",
            gobj_read_integer_attr(gobj, "kc_calls") + 1);
            Ōåō
        SDATA lookup by name, JSON read, JSON write ŌĆö per increment.
    
    After (uint64_t field + mt_stats override):
        priv->st_kc_calls++;
            Ōåō
        Single instruction. No string lookup, no JSON, no SDATA.
    
    The JSON dict is built once, on demand, when an operator runs
    `stats` against the gobj ŌĆö which is exactly when you want to pay
    that cost.
    
