    Fix mbedTLS bad_record_mac: accumulate encrypted records before write
    
    The root cause of bad_record_mac was that mbedtls_ssl_write() called
    send_callback() once per TLS record (~8464 times for large responses),
    each creating an independent io_uring write event. When TCP send buffers
    fill up, partial writes cause requeuing at the io_uring tail, allowing
    later records to be written before earlier ones complete ŌĆö interleaving
    TLS records in the TCP stream and breaking AEAD integrity.
    
    Fix mirrors the OpenSSL wbio model: send_callback() now accumulates
    encrypted records into output_buffer; flush_encrypted_data() submits
    the entire batch as a single on_encrypted_data_cb() call (ŌåÆ one io_uring
    write), eliminating concurrent write interleaving.
    
    Also fix memory leak in both mbedTLS and OpenSSL paths: gbuffer_decref()
    is now called after on_encrypted_data_cb() to release the caller's
    reference (the io_uring write event holds its own via gbuffer_incref).
    
    Added flush_encrypted_data() calls after all mbedtls_ssl_handshake()
    call sites so handshake bytes (ServerHello, Certificate, etc.) are
    sent immediately rather than stuck in the accumulation buffer.
    
    Co-Authored-By: Claude Sonnet 4.6 <noreply@anthropic.com>

