    security: SEC-06 ŌĆö OAuth2 best practices, PKCE, BFF, httpOnly cookies
    
    Problem
    -------
    The old authentication used the Resource Owner Password Credentials
    (ROPC) grant (grant_type=password), which:
    - Required the browser JS to collect and forward user credentials.
    - Stored both access_token and refresh_token in localStorage, making
      them trivially stealable by XSS.
    - Prevented social logins (Google, GitHub, ŌĆ”).
    
    Solution
    --------
    Full OAuth2 Authorization Code + PKCE flow with a Backend For Frontend
    (BFF) so that raw JWTs are never visible to JavaScript.
    
    Frontend (JS):
    - c_login.js: completely rewritten.
      * PKCE flow: generate code_verifier / code_challenge with WebCrypto,
        redirect to Keycloak, handle ?code= callback on return.
      * CSRF protection: state nonce stored in sessionStorage for the
        duration of the OAuth redirect round-trip only; deleted immediately
        after use.
      * No tokens in JS: code is POSTed to the BFF (/auth/callback); the
        BFF exchanges it server-side and writes httpOnly cookies.
      * Refresh / logout go through /auth/refresh and /auth/logout BFF
        endpoints (credentials:"include"); JS only ever sees
        {username, expires_in, refresh_expires_in}.
      * Social login support: kc_idp_hint parameter routes to Google,
        GitHub, or any Keycloak Identity Provider.
      * Removed all localStorage usage and all raw token attributes.
    - backend_config.js: added bff_urls (per hostname) and oauth_providers
      list with kc_idp_hint values.
    - c_yuneta_gui.js: do_connect() called with null jwt; the httpOnly
      cookie is sent automatically by the browser with the WebSocket upgrade.
    
    Backend (C):
    - c_auth_bff.c / c_auth_bff.h (new GClass C_AUTH_BFF):
      * Listens on HTTP port 1801 (separate from WebSocket port 1800).
      * POST /auth/callback ŌĆö PKCE code exchange with Keycloak server-side;
        sets access_token + refresh_token as httpOnly Secure SameSite=Strict
        cookies scoped to the shared hostname (works across ports 1800/1801).
      * POST /auth/refresh ŌĆö reads httpOnly refresh_token cookie, calls
        Keycloak refresh endpoint, overwrites cookies.
      * POST /auth/logout  ŌĆö reads httpOnly refresh_token cookie, calls
        Keycloak logout, clears cookies (Max-Age=0).
      * OPTIONS ŌĆö CORS preflight with Access-Control-Allow-Credentials:true.
      * Requests are serialised in a fixed-size queue; one Keycloak call
        at a time (auth is not a throughput-critical path).
      * Follows the C_TASK + C_PROT_HTTP_CL pattern of c_task_authenticate.c.
    - c_websocket.c: on WebSocket upgrade success (server side), include
      the Cookie header from the HTTP Upgrade request in the EV_ON_OPEN kw
      (http_cookie key).
    - c_ievent_srv.c:
      * New volatile attribute "http_cookie" stores the Cookie from EV_ON_OPEN.
      * ac_identity_card: if jwt is empty in IDENTITY_CARD, extract
        "access_token" from the http_cookie string and inject it into kw
        before calling gobj_authenticate().  This makes the JWT-in-cookie
        path fully transparent to c_authz.c.
    - yunetas_register.c + CMakeLists.txt: register and build C_AUTH_BFF.
    
    Keycloak configuration required (not automated):
    - Standard Flow (Authorization Code): ENABLED
    - Direct Access Grants (ROPC): DISABLED
    - Valid Redirect URIs: app URL + /*
    - Configure Google / GitHub Identity Providers for social login.
    - Set client as public (PKCE) or confidential (add client_secret to
      C_AUTH_BFF attributes for the BFF code exchange).
    
