    mbedtls: fix SIGSEGV use-after-free in flush_clear_data (alive-marker)
    
    flush_clear_data() loops calling on_clear_data_cb() to deliver decrypted
    data to the application.  The callback can trigger a connection close
    (e.g. after receiving an HTTP response), which calls free_secure_filter()
    ŌåÆ GBMEM_FREE(sskt).  On the next loop iteration sskt->ytls is accessed
    on freed memory ŌåÆ SIGSEGV.
    
    Fix with the standard "alive marker" pattern:
    - sskt_t gains a BOOL *alive field (NULL when not in a callback loop).
    - flush_clear_data() stores the address of a stack-local BOOL in
      sskt->alive before iterating; after each on_clear_data_cb() call it
      checks the local variable ŌĆö if FALSE, sskt was freed, so return
      immediately without touching sskt again.
    - free_secure_filter() writes *sskt->alive = FALSE before freeing sskt,
      signalling the stack frame above.
    - Also explicitly initialise sskt->alive and sskt->handshake_informed
      in new_secure_filter() (GBMEM_MALLOC does not zero memory).
    
