    mbedtls: fix SNI + WANT_READ loop to receive server responses
    
    Two bugs prevented the yuneta agent from receiving EV_IDENTITY_CARD_ACK
    from the remote controlcenter when using mbedTLS (worked fine with OpenSSL):
    
    1. Missing SNI: mbedtls_ssl_set_hostname() was never called, so the
       ClientHello contained no server_name extension.  The remote server
       requires SNI to route connections correctly and silently dropped
       IDENTITY_CARD without sending ACK.
    
       Fix: c_tcp.c extracts the hostname from the URL via parse_url() and
       injects it as ssl_server_name into jn_crypto before ytls_init().
       mbedtls.c stores it in ytls_t and calls mbedtls_ssl_set_hostname()
       in new_secure_filter() after mbedtls_ssl_setup() and before the
       initial handshake, enabling the server_name extension in ClientHello.
    
    2. Premature WANT_READ break: after mbedTLS v4.0 silently consumed a
       TLS 1.3 NewSessionTicket (returning WANT_READ instead of the NST
       error code), flush_clear_data() broke out of the read loop leaving
       1200+ bytes of application data (the IDENTITY_CARD_ACK) unprocessed
       in encrypted_buffer.  Those bytes were never forwarded to mbedTLS
       because no further network data arrived to trigger another
       decrypt_data() call.
    
       Fix: in flush_clear_data(), when WANT_READ is returned and
       encrypted_buffer is still non-empty, continue the loop instead of
       breaking so mbedTLS can parse the buffered records.
    
    Co-Authored-By: Claude Sonnet 4.6 <noreply@anthropic.com>

