    mbedtls: handle NewSessionTicket; fix DNS ID validation
    
    Two bugs found by security review of the CONFIG_HAVE_MBEDTLS and
    CONFIG_FULLY_STATIC additions:
    
    1. mbedtls.c flush_clear_data(): TLS 1.3 NewSessionTicket causes disconnect
    
       In TLS 1.3 the server can send a NewSessionTicket post-handshake
       message at any time after the handshake completes.  mbedTLS processes
       the ticket internally and returns MBEDTLS_ERR_SSL_RECEIVED_NEW_SESSION_TICKET
       (-0x7B00) from mbedtls_ssl_read() to inform the caller.  This is NOT
       a fatal error; the caller must simply loop and call mbedtls_ssl_read()
       again to continue reading application data.
    
       The previous code treated every negative return (other than WANT_READ /
       WANT_WRITE) as a fatal TLS error, causing an immediate disconnect with:
         ERROR mbedtls_ssl_read() FAILED error_code=-31488
    
       Fix: catch MBEDTLS_ERR_SSL_RECEIVED_NEW_SESSION_TICKET under its
       #ifdef guard (constant marked experimental in mbedTLS) and `continue`
       the read loop instead of returning -1111.
    
    2. yev_loop.c yuneta_getaddrinfo(): DNS transaction ID not validated
    
       dns_parse_response() never checked that the ID in the UDP response
       matched the ID sent in the query.  A stray or spoofed UDP packet
       arriving on the same socket (same source port) could inject false
       address records.
    
       Fix: add expected_id parameter to dns_parse_response() and reject any
       response whose first two bytes do not match.  Call sites capture the
       ID from yuneta_dns_id before incrementing (qid4 / qid6) and pass it
       to dns_parse_response().
    
    https://claude.ai/code/session_01GicjTFCFFzoEBuoi5nXjrL

